flying saucers on his mind.

00:29:02.700 --> 00:29:05.790 align:middle line:10%
Wilbert Brockhouse Smith,
a senior radio engineer

00:29:05.790 --> 00:29:08.130 align:middle line:10%
at the Canadian
Department of Transport

00:29:08.130 --> 00:29:10.800 align:middle line:10%
was attending a conference.

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:13.920 align:middle line:84%
Smith was doing research
into geomagnetism

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:16.260 align:middle line:84%
and had been interested
in flying saucers

00:29:16.260 --> 00:29:20.910 align:middle line:90%
from the first reports in 1947.

00:29:20.910 --> 00:29:24.660 align:middle line:84%
According to a confidential
memo to his transport superiors

00:29:24.660 --> 00:29:27.030 align:middle line:84%
that was discovered
in the late '70s,

00:29:27.030 --> 00:29:30.510 align:middle line:84%
Smith made discreet inquiries
through the Canadian embassy

00:29:30.510 --> 00:29:34.200 align:middle line:84%
to a high ranking US Defense
Research Board scientist

00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:37.260 align:middle line:90%
Doctor Robert I. Sarbacher.

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:39.960 align:middle line:84%
The memo described
what he learned.

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:42.750 align:middle line:84%
The matter is the most
highly classified subject

00:29:42.750 --> 00:29:45.780 align:middle line:84%
in the United States
government, rating higher even

00:29:45.780 --> 00:29:47.850 align:middle line:90%
than the H bomb.

00:29:47.850 --> 00:29:51.900 align:middle line:84%
